    "2026-07-01 V9m — LoomRegistry drain-state contract (paired with V9m-T): fills the three drain-state writers in src/extension/reload-wiring.ts (drain() sets drained=true per PIC-32; initDrainStateTag() sets drainStateTag=\"shutting-down\" iff currently undefined; markRuntimeDegraded() sets drainStateTag=\"degraded-needs-reload\" unconditionally) and the routing/dispatch surface in src/extension/drain-state.ts. routeDrainStateArm maps the six (drained, tag) tuples onto the closed three arms (PIC-29): tag \"degraded-needs-reload\" → arm (c); tag \"shutting-down\" or drained → arm (b); steady-state (false, undefined) → arm (a); no fourth arm (PIC-30). shouldShortCircuitShutdown is the disjunction drained === true || tag !== undefined (idempotent, fires on every non-steady tuple). routeSlashDispatchWithReadFailover wraps the slash-site readDrainState in a broad try/catch and routes a read throw to arm (c) (PIC-31); evalShutdownShortCircuitWithReadFailover wraps the handler-entry read and treats a throw as steady-state (predicate not fired → full teardown). resolveSlashDispatch routes arm (a) to the entry-table lookup, returning the dispatched loom on a hit and the fixed \"loom /<name>: superseded; /reload to refresh\" note on a miss. The two read-failover catch (e: unknown) sites carry // allow-broad-catch: PIC-31. No module-level mutable state, no ambient primitive / Promise combinator / Sync call. No new diagnostics-registry codes. All 14 V9m-T tests green; full suite 667 green, typecheck + lint + H2a/H3a/broad-catch gates clean.",
    "2026-07-01 V9m-T — LoomRegistry drain-state contract tests (paired V9m impl): extends src/extension/reload-wiring.ts LoomRegistry with the closed four-method drain-state surface (backing fields #drained/#drainStateTag; drain()/initDrainStateTag()/markRuntimeDegraded() inert no-op stubs, readDrainState() the real field-read) plus the DrainStateTag/DrainStateSnapshot types, and adds src/extension/drain-state.ts — routeDrainStateArm (inert stub → always arm (a)), shouldShortCircuitShutdown (inert stub → always false), routeSlashDispatchWithReadFailover / evalShutdownShortCircuitWithReadFailover (inert stubs ignoring the read), resolveSlashDispatch (inert stub → always dispatch), and the fixed shuttingDownNote/degradedNote/supersededNote templates — plus tests/drain-state-contract.test.ts with 14 tests pinning drain-state-contract.md (PIC-29/30/31/32) and registration-steps.md#superseded-entry-dispatch. PIC-29: each of the six (drained, tag) tuples routes to its closed three-arm enumeration value (mutually exclusive, exhaustive), and the short-circuit predicate drained === true || tag !== undefined fires on every tuple except steady-state (false, undefined). PIC-30: routing the full six-tuple space yields exactly three arms (no fourth arm), the readDrainState snapshot exposes exactly drained/tag (no third boolean field), and the post-failed-handler (false, undefined) tuple still routes to arm (a) (no arm-specific gate). PIC-31: a slash-site read-failure fails safe onto arm (c), a handler-entry read-failure fails safe to steady-state (predicate not fired → full teardown). PIC-32: LoomRegistry.drain() flips drained to true and the short-circuit predicate is idempotent. Superseded-entry dispatch: a steady-state dispatch with a dropped entry reaches arm (a), the entry-table lookup misses, and the fixed \"loom /<name>: superseded; /reload to refresh\" note is returned. No new diagnostics-registry codes. Inert stub seam: no module-level mutable state, no broad catch / ambient primitive / Promise combinator / Sync call. Typecheck + lint clean; 10 of the 14 tests red on their own primary assertions because the V9m body is absent — fail-red-for-the-intended-reason; the other 657 tests stay green."
